body:
Hi @EnricoBeltramo thanks for your feedback. Currently onnxruntime web does not support a model that uses Float16 as input/output tensor type. I am not sure how the model is generated; but there should be an option for exporter/converter to allow the model to use float32 as input/output type.

please let me know if you need further help.

Thank you for support. Here: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/js/web I saw that onnx web assembly backend support all operators, so I hoped that using tihs interface, it should work. But setting wasm as backend with follow code:
const session = await ort.InferenceSession.create(modelpath, {executionProviders: ['wasm']});
I have follow error:
Error: no available backend found. ERR: [wasm] RuntimeError: abort(CompileError: WebAssembly.instantiate(): expected magic word 00 61 73 6d, found 3c 21 44 4f @+0). Build with -s ASSERTIONS=1 for more info.
What should do to use wasm interface?

This error indicates the initialization of web assembly is failed. The problem is probably because the .wasm file is not loaded correctly. could you check in your devtool if the file `ort-wasm*.wasm` is requested and responded 200 OK by server?

@EnricoBeltramo @ManuelGTM could you please share more information, including:
- how do you set up your web app project
   - is it using a well-known framework like react/vuejs?
   - do you have "onnxruntime-web" in your dependencies in package.json?
- how do you deploy your project
   - are you deploying a dev version or a prod version
   - how is your settings in webpack.config.js (or for other bundler)

Also, could you please check the browser's devtool to see what is the URL it requires for the .wasm file.

I will take further investigation based on those information. I think it is a deployment problem, but at least we can improve the documents.

@ManuelGTM I have the same setup as you and had the same issue. If you look at the [webpack config file](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/main/js/quick-start_onnxruntime-web-bundler/webpack.config.js) for the example project, you'll see they are using the copy webpack plugin. I was able to get the example to work by copying over the wasm files `node_modules/onnxruntime-web/dist/*.wasm` to `public/static/js/`. You can add the copy-wepack-plugin to the override config but make sure the copy-webpack-plugin version works with webpack 4 since you're using react create app.

issue.title: Issue loading onnx model to wasm using `onnxruntime-web`

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body: **Describe the bug** I have read #9322 and followed the steps. Following the steps I tried to load an onnx model to wasm instead of webgl (because my model have some layers which cannot be resolved on webgl). I got the error `Error: no available backend found. ERR: [wasm] RuntimeError: Aborted(CompileError: WebAssembly.instantiate(): expected magic word 00 61 73 6d, found 3c 21 44 4f @+0). Build with -s ASSERTIONS=1 for more info.` **Urgency** I wish I can solve this problem by **mid May** for presentation. **System information** - OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04 - ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary - ONNX Runtime version: latest - Python version: 3.6.9 - CUDA/cuDNN version: 11.4 **To Reproduce** - Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior. - Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation. I have a project built by vue.js. I have installed onnxruntime-web and saved into package.json: ```JavaScript "onnxruntime": "^1.7.0", "onnxruntime-node": "^1.11.0", "onnxruntime-web": "^1.11.0", ``` I added the plugin to `vue-config.js`: ```JavaScript const CopyWebpackPlugin = require('copy-webpack-plugin') module.exports = { configureWebpack: { module: { rules: [ { test: /\.txt$/i, use: 'raw-loader', } ] }, plugins: [ new CopyWebpackPlugin([ { from: "node_modules/onnxruntime-web/dist/*.wasm", to : "[name][ext]" }, ]) ] }, devServer: { proxy: { '^/filter-api': { ... ``` I tried to load the model in a JavaScript source file: ```JavaScript import { InferenceSession } from 'onnxruntime-web' ... const modelUrl = '/onnx/ai_sharp.onnx' await InferenceSession.create(modelUrl, { executionProviders: ['wasm'], }) ... ``` The model is actually the generation model in [CycleGAN](https://github.com/junyanz/pytorch-CycleGAN-and-pix2pix): ```python model = [nn.ReflectionPad2d(3), nn.Conv2d(input_nc, ngf, kernel_size=7, padding=0, bias=use_bias), norm_layer(ngf), nn.ReLU(True)] n_downsampling = 2 for i in range(n_downsampling): # add downsampling layers mult = 2 ** i model += [nn.Conv2d(ngf * mult, ngf * mult * 2, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1, bias=use_bias), norm_layer(ngf * mult * 2), nn.ReLU(True)] mult = 2 ** n_downsampling for i in range(n_blocks): # add ResNet blocks model += [ResnetBlock(ngf * mult, padding_type=padding_type, norm_layer=norm_layer, use_dropout=use_dropout, use_bias=use_bias)] for i in range(n_downsampling): # add upsampling layers mult = 2 ** (n_downsampling - i) model += [nn.ConvTranspose2d(ngf * mult, int(ngf * mult / 2), kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=0, output_padding=0, bias=use_bias), norm_layer(int(ngf * mult / 2)), nn.ReLU(True)] model += [nn.ReflectionPad2d(3)] model += [nn.Conv2d(ngf, output_nc, kernel_size=7, padding=0)] model += [nn.Tanh()] self.model = nn.Sequential(*model) ``` When I ran the server and opened in Chrome, I found in the developer tool that these files are fetched: But in the console I got the errors: ``` wasm streaming compile failed: TypeError: Failed to execute 'compile' on 'WebAssembly': Incorrect response MIME type. Expected 'application/wasm'. falling back to ArrayBuffer instantiation failed to asynchronously prepare wasm: CompileError: WebAssembly.instantiate(): expected magic word 00 61 73 6d, found 3c 21 44 4f @+0 ort-web.min.js?f1d4:6 Aborted(CompileError: WebAssembly.instantiate(): expected magic word 00 61 73 6d, found 3c 21 44 4f @+0) ``` Back to the JavaScript source file, when I loaded the model with normal `webgl` backend, I got `TypeError: cannot resolve operator 'ConvTranspose' with opsets: ai.onnx v9`, which is expected becaue this operation is not supported. **Expected behavior** Successfully load the model on wasm backend.

I was able to get the example to work by copying over the wasm files `node_modules/onnxruntime-web/dist/*.wasm` to `public/static/js/`.
